<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">flowering in May and fruiting in September-October.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
in openings of 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus nigra" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pinus nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
(Figure 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Distribution of the taxa. (square) Crataegus azarolus var. senobaaensis; (star) Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii var. nov. (circle) Crataegus yaltirikii (Near East topographic map-blank. svg)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.122.33002.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/302257" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">3</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doenmez &amp; Oezderin" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
is endemic to 
<normalizedToken originalValue="İzmir">Izmir</normalizedToken>
; it has a narrow distribution at 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gölcük">Goelcuek</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ecology and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doenmez &amp; Oezderin" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
grows in openings of 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus nigra" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pinus nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest between 1050 and 1120 m elevation. The basic vegetation type is maquis at lower elevations of the area. Besides this, 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus nigra" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pinus nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forest replaces it at higher altitudes and steppe vegetation dominates above the tree zone.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The epithet of this new variety denotes the collection area, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Ödemiş">Oedemis</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Preliminary conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doenmez &amp; Oezderin" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">Crataegus monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
should be assigned to &quot;Critically Endangered&quot;, (CR B2ab(i,ii,iii,iv), D) according to the 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Flora of China" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B11" refString="IUCN, 2017. Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 12. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Standards and Petitions Subcommittee. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 12. Prepared by the Standards and Petitions Subcommittee." url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2017">IUCN (2017)</bibRefCitation>
threat categories. The area of occupancy is estimated to be less than 10 km2 and the examined specimens are known only from alongside the road. The location is close to the picnic area of the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gölcük">Goelcuek</normalizedToken>
Lake and is under threat from fire, cutting and other anthropogenic effects.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Two new varieties have been published by 
<bibRefCitation author="Browicz, K" editor="Davis, PH" journalOrPublisher="Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="133 - 147" refId="B1" refString="Browicz, K, 1972. Crataegus L. (Rosaceae). In: Davis, PH, Ed., Flora of Turkey and the East Aegean Islands. Edinburgh University Press, Edinburgh: 133 - 147" title="Crataegus L. (Rosaceae)" volumeTitle="Flora of Turkey and the East Aegean Islands." year="1972">Browicz (1972)</bibRefCitation>
from Turkey under the species name of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. aronia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aronia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. aronia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. These two varieties were reduced to synonym by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" author="Christensen, KI" journalOrPublisher="Plant Systematics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B3" refString="Christensen, KI, 1992. Revision of Crataegussect.Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35. https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" title="Revision of Crataegussect. Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" year="1992">Christensen (1992)</bibRefCitation>
with their published name and he accepted the name 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="azarolus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus azarolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. aronia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aronia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. aronia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Taxonomic decisions of Christensen have been based solely on herbarium material. During the taxonomic revision of the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the first author had the opportunity to observe these varieties in their habitats alongside the complete set of morphological variations of the species. Moreover, morphological studies on the large set of herbarium material in the above-mentioned herbaria and fieldwork from Greece to Iran provided more opportunity to observe all kinds of variation of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. azarolus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="azarolus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. azarolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the closely related taxa. Consequently, based on field observations and herbarium studies on the collected materials, these two varieties, namely 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Doenmez" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Browicz" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus var. dentata" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="azarolus" variety="dentata">Crataegus azarolus L. var. dentata</taxonomicName>
(Browicz) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Dönmez">Doenmez</normalizedToken>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Doenmez" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Browicz" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" infraspecific-rank="var." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus var. minuta" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="azarolus" variety="minuta">Crataegus azarolus L. var. minuta</taxonomicName>
(Browicz) 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Dönmez">Doenmez</normalizedToken>
should be accepted as distinct taxa and they should be given as new combinations under the species name of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus azarolus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="azarolus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus azarolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus monogyna" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most polymorphic species amongst the Eurasian 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa with respect to leaf morphology and indumentum. Due to local variations of the species and species concepts by the authors who studied 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, many new taxa have been described. In addition, new combinations and alteration of their status have been made. Based on these taxonomic and nomenclatural novelties, both taxonomic and nomenclatural synonyms of about 200 names have been listed by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" author="Christensen, KI" journalOrPublisher="Plant Systematics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B3" refString="Christensen, KI, 1992. Revision of Crataegussect.Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35. https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" title="Revision of Crataegussect. Crataegus and nothosect. Crataeguineae (Rosaceae-Maloideae) in the Old World. Systematic Botany Monographs: 35." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/25027810" year="1992">Christensen (1992)</bibRefCitation>
. In 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, extensive variations in leaf morphology and indumentum are present, whereas variations in fruit colour are limited. Fruit colour of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is clearly red and/or with degrees of red. Specimens of the new variety, 
<taxonomicName genus="C." infraspecific-rank="var." lsidName="C. monogyna var. odemisii" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="variety" species="monogyna" variety="odemisii">C. monogyna var. odemisii</taxonomicName>
are yellow. Red and various degrees of red colour for fruit of infraspecific 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa have been observed by the second author and they have hundreds of representative specimens for these fruit colours in the above-mentioned herbaria. According to observations on the fruit colour of single pyrened 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxon, it is a constant character and unique in the infraspecific taxa of 
<taxonomicName genus="C." lsidName="C. monogyna" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="monogyna">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. monogyna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Hence, it is worthwhile accepting this population as a separate taxonomic status, as a variety.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Crataegus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Crataegus yaltirikii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="yaltirikii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Crataegus yaltirikii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Dönmez">Doenmez</normalizedToken>
is a recently described new species from southeast Turkey and we found a new population of the species on the Taurus Mountain ranges, nearly 400 km away from the type locality. Climatic conditions of these two localities are different; the type locality is a cold and snowy area, whereas the recently discovered locality is characterised by hot and dry summers, rainy and warm winters. We have not yet obtained molecular works on these disjunct populations. Besides this, we assume that these populations should be local ecotypes of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
